---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    .step-list { counter-reset: step; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 14px; }
    .step {
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      padding: 16px 18px;
      background: var(--card);
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 36px 1fr;
      gap: 14px;
    }
    .step-num {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 13px;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
      border-radius: 6px;
      height: 28px; width: 28px;
      display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
      background: var(--muted);
    }
    .step-title { font-weight: 600; font-size: 14px; margin-bottom: 4px; }
    .step-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.55; }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="20 · Sardis Connect — Sardis Canvas" currentId="sardis-connect">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 20 · Extended</span>
        <h1>Sardis Connect</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          Make any API agent-ready in three lines of code. The merchant ships USD,
          the agent pays in stablecoins, Sardis handles every crypto primitive in between.
          This canvas explains what Connect is, how it differs from Pay with Sardis, and how
          the full onboarding flow works end-to-end.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          <strong>Pay with Sardis</strong> is a customer-facing checkout (buyer clicks "Pay with Sardis" on a merchant site).
          <strong>Sardis Connect</strong> is the merchant-facing inverse — a drop-in SDK that turns any HTTP API into an
          agent-payable service: discovery, payment, verification, and USD settlement. Merchant integrates in
          <code>5 minutes</code>, never touches a wallet, receives USD in their connected bank account.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Who uses it -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Audience</div>
          <h2>Who actually ships Sardis Connect.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Connect is a B2B2Agent wedge. The merchant is any company that already runs an HTTP API and wants
            AI agents as a new revenue channel — without learning what a gas fee is.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">AI API providers</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Text-generation, embeddings, analysis, transcription, image, speech APIs. Today they gatekeep with
              API keys + human-signed Stripe subscriptions. With Connect, every endpoint gets a price and an agent
              can pay per call — no signup, no CAPTCHA, no credit card form.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Data and scraping APIs</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              The long tail of priced HTTP APIs (proxies, weather, FX, company data). The per-request monetization
              loop is the native Connect shape: agent discovers via <code>/.well-known/sardis.json</code>, pays
              $0.001 per call, uses it.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">SaaS platforms exposing agent features</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              A traditional SaaS (CRM, analytics, ticketing) adds Connect to bill agents for programmatic access.
              Human users stay on the existing subscription plan; agents get a per-call plan without any pricing-page
              gymnastics.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Services in the OSP ecosystem</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              A provider implementing Open Service Protocol (OSP) can declare <code>sardis_wallet</code> in
              <code>accepted_payment_methods</code>. Connect is the drop-in library that makes that declaration
              real — payment, verification, settlement. See Canvas 21 · OSP Integration.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Integration flow -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">The Flow</div>
          <h2>Merchant onboarding, end to end.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Four moving parts: the merchant app, the Connect SDK, the Sardis API (merchant checkout),
            and the merchant's connected bank rail. The merchant touches three of the four; Sardis orchestrates the fourth.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
sequenceDiagram
    participant M as Merchant app (FastAPI)
    participant SC as sardis-connect SDK
    participant AG as AI Agent
    participant SA as Sardis API
    participant ST as Bank rail

    Note over M,SC: 1. One-time setup
    M->>SA: POST /merchants/register
    SA-->>M: merchant_id + mch_live_xxx key
    M->>ST: Express onboarding (hosted)
    ST-->>M: acct_xxx, charges_enabled=true
    M->>SC: SardisConnect(api_key, merchant_id)
    M->>SC: sardis.price("/api/generate", "0.05")
    M->>M: app.include_router(sardis.router)

    Note over AG,M: 2. Agent runtime
    AG->>M: GET /.well-known/sardis.json
    M-->>AG: manifest {endpoints, prices, accepts}
    AG->>M: POST /sardis/pay {endpoint, mandate_id}
    M->>SA: POST /merchant-checkout/sessions
    SA-->>M: session_id + client_secret
    M-->>AG: PaySession
    AG->>SA: pay(session_id) via SDK + mandate
    SA->>SA: policy + KYC + mandate checks
    SA->>SA: USDC settlement on Base/Tempo

    Note over SA,ST: 3. Settlement
    SA->>ST: Connect Transfer (USD)
    ST-->>M: auto-payout to bank
    AG->>M: POST /api/generate (X-Sardis-Session)
    M->>SC: paywall verifies session
    SC->>SA: GET /sessions/{id}
    SA-->>SC: status=paid
    M-->>AG: 200 OK (API response)
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Python quickstart -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Python SDK</div>
          <h2>Three lines in FastAPI.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Straight from <code>packages/sardis-connect/README.md</code>. The router exposes three endpoints:
            agent discovery, payment session creation, and payment verification.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-block">
<pre><code>from fastapi import FastAPI
from sardis_connect import SardisConnect

app = FastAPI()

# 1. Initialize with your merchant credentials
sardis = SardisConnect(
    api_key="mch_live_xxx",
    merchant_id="merch_xxx",
    service_name="My AI API",
)

# 2. Define priced endpoints (or sardis.meter() for per-unit)
sardis.price("/api/generate", amount="0.05", description="Generate text")
sardis.price("/api/analyze", amount="0.10", description="Analyze data")

# 3. Mount the router
app.include_router(sardis.router)
</code></pre>
        </div>
        <table class="data mt-16">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Endpoint</th><th>Method</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>/.well-known/sardis.json</code></td><td>GET</td><td>Agent discovery manifest — name, accepted rails, endpoints, prices.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/sardis/pay</code></td><td>POST</td><td>Create a <code>merchant-checkout</code> session; returns <code>session_id</code> + <code>client_secret</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/sardis/verify</code></td><td>POST</td><td>Look up session status; returns <code>&#123; verified, amount, payer_id &#125;</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/sardis/webhooks</code></td><td>POST</td><td>Signed (HMAC-SHA256) webhook receiver for payment events.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/sardis/usage</code></td><td>POST</td><td>Report metered usage (tokens/units) for per-unit pricing — see <code>SardisConnect.meter()</code>.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="text-muted mt-16" style="max-width:720px;">
          Protect any endpoint with the <code>SardisPaywall</code> FastAPI dependency — the client passes
          <code>X-Sardis-Session: mcs_…</code> and the dependency verifies status against the Sardis API before the
          handler runs. Source: <code>packages/sardis-connect/src/sardis_connect/middleware.py</code>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- JS quickstart -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Node SDK</div>
          <h2>Express / Node.js, same three lines.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Published as <code>@sardis/connect</code>. Source in
            <code>packages/sardis-connect-js/src/middleware.ts</code>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-block">
<pre><code>import express from "express";
import &#123; sardisConnect &#125; from "@sardis/connect";

const app = express();

const sardis = sardisConnect(&#123;
  apiKey: "mch_live_xxx",
  merchantId: "merch_xxx",
  serviceName: "My AI API",
  baseUrl: "https://api.example.com",
&#125;);

sardis.price("/api/generate", "0.05", "Generate text");
sardis.price("/api/analyze", "0.10", "Analyze data");

app.use(sardis.middleware());
</code></pre>
        </div>
        <p class="text-muted mt-16" style="max-width:720px;">
          The middleware hands off to <code>next()</code> for anything that isn't a Sardis route, so it composes
          cleanly with existing Express apps. The manifest declares <code>accepts: ["sardis", "x402", "mpp"]</code>
          — agents can choose whichever rail they prefer; the server-side flow is identical.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- E2E demo walkthrough -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Reference Demo</div>
          <h2>The E2E script, step by step.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            <code>demos/sardis_connect_e2e_demo.py</code> walks the full lifecycle in ~320 lines.
            Each step maps to one subsystem.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="step-list">
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div>
              <div class="step-title">Merchant registration</div>
              <div class="step-desc">
                <code>Merchant(name, settlement_preference="stripe_connect", mcc_code="5734")</code>. Produces a
                <code>merchant_id</code> and an API key in the <code>mch_live_…</code> namespace. Backed by
                <code>sardis-core/merchant.py</code> and the <code>merchants</code> router.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div>
              <div class="step-title">Merchant onboarding</div>
              <div class="step-desc">
                Hosted Stripe Express flow (KYB + bank details). On return: <code>charges_enabled</code>,
                <code>payouts_enabled</code>, <code>onboarding_state=complete</code>. The merchant record is
                stamped with <code>stripe_account_id</code>; this is where USD will land.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div>
              <div class="step-title">Agent discovery</div>
              <div class="step-desc">
                Agent does <code>GET /.well-known/sardis.json</code>. The manifest is built by
                <code>SardisConnect._get_manifest()</code> from the in-process endpoint registry plus
                <code>accepts: ["sardis", "x402", "mpp"]</code>.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">4</div>
            <div>
              <div class="step-title">Spending mandate check</div>
              <div class="step-desc">
                Before calling <code>/sardis/pay</code>, the agent's <code>SpendingMandate</code> is evaluated:
                per-tx, daily, monthly caps, <code>merchant_scope</code> allowlist, <code>allowed_rails</code>.
                Denials include a machine-readable reason code. See Canvas 08 · Policy Engine.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">5</div>
            <div>
              <div class="step-title">Natural-language policy</div>
              <div class="step-desc">
                The demo parses phrases like "Maximum $50 per day on AI API calls" via
                <code>RegexPolicyParser</code> in <code>sardis-core/nl_policy_parser.py</code>. The parsed
                structure becomes a signed mandate.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">6</div>
            <div>
              <div class="step-title">Multi-protocol execution</div>
              <div class="step-desc">
                Same agent, same mandate, three rails: direct USDC (Base/Tempo), x402
                (HTTP 402 on micropayments), and MPP (Stripe session). Connect is rail-agnostic because the
                manifest advertises all three and the Sardis orchestrator selects the best fit.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">7</div>
            <div>
              <div class="step-title">Settlement to USD</div>
              <div class="step-desc">
                Sardis settlement engine fires a transfer to <code>acct_…</code>; Stripe's
                auto-payout pushes USD to the merchant's bank. Reconciliation enqueued in the Postgres
                reconciliation queue (see Canvas 10 · Settlement &amp; Chains).
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Merchant payout rail -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Settlement Provider</div>
          <h2>Why the merchant never touches crypto.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Why a bank-connected merchant account</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              The merchant already trusts Stripe for card payments. Connect's Express account model
              amortizes KYB/KYC across their existing compliance stack, so Sardis does not rebuild it.
              The tradeoff is Stripe's fee on the USD leg — Sardis eats none of that margin on the crypto
              leg (<code>gasless</code> via Circle Paymaster, USDC native).
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Alternative rails</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              EU merchants can opt into Striga (SEPA + vIBANs). Multi-rail merchants can use Bridge
              (ACH/SEPA/PIX). Lightspark is wired for Lightning. The <code>settlement_preference</code> field on
              the <code>Merchant</code> record is the toggle — abstracted behind
              <code>sardis-core/settlement</code>.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Pricing / settlement model -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Economics</div>
          <h2>Pricing + settlement model.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Mechanism</th><th>How it works</th><th>When to use</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Fixed price</td><td><code>sardis.price(path, amount)</code> — agent pays the posted price per call.</td><td>Predictable endpoints: generation, embeddings, search.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Metered (per-unit)</td><td><code>sardis.meter(path, per_unit, unit)</code> — agent calls, merchant reports <code>units</code> via <code>/sardis/usage</code>, Sardis computes charge.</td><td>LLM completions (tokens), vision (pixels), data egress (bytes).</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Platform fee</td><td>Sardis takes a flat percentage on the USDC leg. Stored as <code>platform_fee_amount</code> on each session. Breakdown exposed to both sides.</td><td>How Sardis monetizes. Transparent on every receipt.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Merchant payout</td><td>Transfer to merchant bank → auto-payout; configurable schedule (daily/weekly).</td><td>US default. Swap to Striga/Bridge for EU/multi-rail.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Comparison vs Pay with Sardis -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Two Products, One Rail</div>
          <h2>Sardis Connect vs. Pay with Sardis.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Both sit on the same <code>merchant-checkout</code> session primitive, but the audience and ergonomics
            diverge. Don't conflate them in sales conversations.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th></th><th>Sardis Connect</th><th>Pay with Sardis (Checkout)</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Who calls it</td><td>An AI agent, programmatically</td><td>A human buyer, in a browser</td></tr>
            <tr><td>UI</td><td>None — JSON over HTTP</td><td>Product-private hosted checkout client backed by public session APIs</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Discovery</td><td><code>/.well-known/sardis.json</code> on the merchant domain</td><td>Merchant-issued checkout link / embedded button</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Payer source</td><td>Agent's Sardis wallet + signed mandate</td><td>External wallet (WalletConnect, Coinbase, MetaMask) or Sardis <code>wal_…</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Auth</td><td>Merchant <code>mch_live_…</code> key + session <code>client_secret</code></td><td>Session <code>client_secret</code>; merchant endpoints use <code>require_principal</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Settlement</td><td>Bank rail → USD</td><td>Same settlement engine; Stripe/Striga/Bridge</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Typical ticket</td><td>$0.001 – $10 per call</td><td>$5 – $500 per order</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SDK</td><td><code>sardis-connect</code> (py) + <code>@sardis/connect</code> (js)</td><td>Hosted client package lives in the private product repo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Canvas</td><td>This page</td><td>Canvas 11 · Checkout &amp; Merchants</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Key files -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Source of Truth</div>
          <h2>Key files.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>File</th><th>Role</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-connect/src/sardis_connect/middleware.py</code></td><td>The FastAPI router — manifest, pay, verify, webhook, usage, paywall dependency.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-connect/src/sardis_connect/models.py</code></td><td><code>PricedEndpoint</code>, <code>PricingModel</code>, <code>ServiceManifest</code>, <code>UsageRecord</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-connect/README.md</code></td><td>The quickstart; source of the Python example above.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-connect-js/src/middleware.ts</code></td><td>Node/Express middleware; same three routes, hand-rolled with <code>fetch</code> to avoid SDK bloat.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-connect-js/src/types.ts</code></td><td>TS types shared with the Python models by contract.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/api/src/sardis_api/routers/merchants.py</code></td><td>Merchant registration + key issuance. Upstream of every Connect flow.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/api/src/sardis_api/routers/service_directory.py</code></td><td>Registry side: where discovered services can be listed globally.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>demos/sardis_connect_e2e_demo.py</code></td><td>The seven-step reference walkthrough.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Cross-refs -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Go deeper</div>
          <h2>Follow-ups.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/checkout">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">11 · Product</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Checkout &amp; Merchants</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">The buyer-facing sibling of Connect. Public session API, webhook, and settlement contract.</div>
          </a>
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/osp-integration">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">21 · Extended</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">OSP Integration</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">Where Connect becomes the <code>sardis_wallet</code> payment method inside the OSP service-discovery standard.</div>
          </a>
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/policy-engine">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">08 · Flows</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Policy Engine</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">How the agent's natural-language mandate resolves into the pay/verify gate that Connect sits behind.</div>
          </a>
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/protocols">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">13 · Product</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Protocol Gateway</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">x402, MPP, AP2 — the three rails the Connect manifest advertises as <code>accepts</code>.</div>
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>
</Canvas>
